<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1946-05-21T14:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1946-05-21T14:00:00-05:00" n="708" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d708">
                    <note rend="inline" type="source">893.51/5–1246: Telegram</note>
                    <head>
                        <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                            Consul General at Shanghai</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Davis</hi></persName>)</head>
                    <opener>
                        <dateline rendition="#right">
                            <placeName>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1946-05-21T15:00:00-04:00">May 21, 1946—3
                                p.m.</date>
                        </dateline>
                    </opener>
                    <p>888. As Dept understands proposal in Urtel 827, May 12, additional credit if
                        granted should be on condition that no exchange be allocated for purchase
                        non-American cotton until a further $7 million has been <pb facs="0997" n="987" xml:id="pg_987"/> allocated for American cotton thus assuring
                        total American sales of 47 million. Dept believes proposal inappropriate and
                        in conflict with principles American trade program. However, sentiment in
                        Eximbank seems adverse to Chinese request but no action taken.</p>
                    <closer>
                        <signed>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Byrnes</hi>
                        </signed>
                    </closer>
                </div>
                </body></text></TEI>